span><div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"2"=
 id=3D"ref217476" data-has-spy=3D"true"> <h1 class=3D"h2">Ancient geometry:=
 abstract and applied</h1><!--[TOC]--> <div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-targe=
t"></div><section data-level=3D"3" id=3D"ref217477" data-has-spy=3D"true"> =
<h2 class=3D"h3">The three classical problems</h2> <!--[PREMOD1]--><span cl=
ass=3D"marker PREMOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">In ad=
dition to proving mathematical theorems, ancient mathematicians constructed=
 various geometrical objects. <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/biograp=
hy/Euclid-Greek-mathematician" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-p=
review=3D"true">Euclid</a> arbitrarily restricted the tools of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.britannica.com/technology/construction" class=3D"md-crosslink au=
toxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">construction</a> to a straightedge (an =
unmarked ruler) and a compass. The restriction made three problems of parti=
cular interest (to double a cube, to trisect an <a class=3D"md-dictionary-l=
ink md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"arbitrary" href=3D"https://www.br=
itannica.com/dictionary/arbitrary" data-type=3D"EB">arbitrary</a> angle, an=
d to <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/square-mathematics" clas=
s=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">square</a> a circle=
) very difficult=E2=80=94in fact, impossible. Various methods of constructi=
on using other means were devised in the classical period, and efforts, alw=
ays unsuccessful, using straightedge and compass persisted for the next 2,0=
00 years. In 1837 the French mathematician Pierre Laurent Wantzel proved th=
at doubling the cube and trisecting the angle are impossible, and in 1880 t=
he German mathematician <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/biography/Fer=
dinand-von-Lindemann" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Fe=
rdinand von Lindemann</a> showed that squaring the circle is impossible, as=
 a consequence of his <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/proof-log=
ic" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">proof</a> t=
hat <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/pi-mathematics" class=3D"=
md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">=CF=80 is a transcendental number=
</a>.</p><!--[MOD1]--><span class=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span> <div c=
lass=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"4" id=3D"ref2=
17478" data-has-spy=3D"true"> <h2 class=3D"h4">Doubling the <span id=3D"ref=
726458"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/cube-mathemati=
cs" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">cube</a></h2> <!--[P=
REMOD2]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topi=
c-paragraph">The Vedic scriptures made the cube the most advisable form of =
altar for anyone who wanted to supplicate in the same place twice. The rule=
s of ritual required that the altar for the second plea have the same shape=
 but twice the volume of the first. If the sides of the original and derive=
d altars are <em>a</em> and <em>b</em>, respectively, then <em>b</em><sup>3=
</sup> =3D 2<em>a</em><sup>3</sup>. The problem came to the Greeks together=
 with its ceremonial content. An oracle disclosed that the citizens of Delo=
s could free themselves of a plague merely by replacing an existing altar b=
y one twice its size. The Delians applied to Plato. He replied that the ora=
cle did not mean that the gods wanted a larger altar but that they had inte=
nded =E2=80=9Cto shame the Greeks for their neglect of <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.britannica.com/science/mathematics" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " dat=
a-show-preview=3D"true">mathematics</a> and their <a class=3D"md-dictionary=
-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"contempt" href=3D"https://www.m=
erriam-webster.com/dictionary/contempt" data-type=3D"MW">contempt</a> for g=
eometry.=E2=80=9D With this blend of Vedic practice, Greek <a class=3D"md-d=
ictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"myth" href=3D"https://=
www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/myth" data-type=3D"MW">myth</a>, and aca=
demic manipulation, the problem of the duplication of the cube took a leadi=
ng place in the formation of Greek geometry.</p><!--[MOD2]--><span class=3D=
"marker MOD2 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD3]--><span class=3D"marker PREM=
OD3 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"><span id=3D"ref726475">=
</span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/biography/Hippocrates-of-Chios=
" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Hippocrates of Chios</=
a>, who wrote an early <em>Elements</em> about 450 <span class=3D"text-smal=
lcaps">bce</span>, took the first steps in cracking the altar problem. He r=
educed the duplication to finding two mean proportionals between 1 and 2, t=
hat is, to finding lines <em>x</em> and <em>y</em> in the <a href=3D"https:=
//www.britannica.com/science/ratio" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-s=
how-preview=3D"true">ratio</a> 1:<em>x</em> =3D <em>x</em>:<em>y</em> =3D <=
em>y</em>:2. After the intervention of the Delian oracle, several geometers=
 around Plato=E2=80=99s Academy found complicated ways of generating mean p=
roportionals.</p><!--[MOD3]--><span class=3D"marker MOD3 mod-inline"></span=
> <!--[PREMOD4]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD4 mod-inline"></span><p class=
=3D"topic-paragraph">A few generations later, <a href=3D"https://www.britan=
nica.com/biography/Eratosthenes" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=
=3D"true">Eratosthenes of Cyrene</a> (<em>c.</em> 276=E2=80=93<em>c.</em> 1=
94 <span class=3D"text-smallcaps">bce</span>) devised a simple instrument w=
ith moving parts that could produce approximate mean proportionals.</p><!--=
[MOD4]--><span class=3D"marker MOD4 mod-inline"></span> </section> <div cla=
ss=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"4" id=3D"ref217=
479" data-has-spy=3D"true"> <h2 class=3D"h4">Trisecting the <span id=3D"ref=
726495"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/angle-mathemat=
ics" class=3D"md-crosslink ">angle</a></h2> <!--[PREMOD5]--><span class=3D"=
marker PREMOD5 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">The Egyptian=
s told time at night by the rising of 12 asterisms (constellations), each r=
equiring on average two hours to rise. In order to obtain more convenient i=
ntervals, the Egyptians subdivided each of their asterisms into three parts=
, or decans. That presented the problem of trisection. It is not known whet=
her the second celebrated problem of <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dict=
ionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"archaic" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster=
.com/dictionary/archaic" data-type=3D"MW">archaic</a> Greek geometry, the t=
risection of any given angle, arose from the difficulty of the decan, but i=
t is likely that it came from some problem in angular measure.</p><!--[MOD5=
]--><span class=3D"marker MOD5 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD6]--><span cl=
ass=3D"marker PREMOD6 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Sever=
al geometers of Plato=E2=80=99s time tried their hands at trisection. Altho=
ugh no one succeeded in finding a solution with straightedge and compass, t=
hey did succeed with a mechanical device and by a trick. The mechanical dev=
ice, perhaps never built, creates what the ancient geometers called a <span=
 id=3D"ref726496"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/quad=
ratrix-of-Hippias" class=3D"md-crosslink ">quadratrix</a>. Invented by a ge=
ometer known as <span id=3D"ref726497"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britan=
nica.com/biography/Hippias-of-Elis" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previ=
ew=3D"true">Hippias of Elis</a> (flourished 5th century <span class=3D"text=
-smallcaps">bce</span>), the quadratrix is a <a href=3D"https://www.britann=
ica.com/science/curve" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=
=3D"true">curve</a> traced by the point of intersection between two moving =
lines, one rotating uniformly through a right angle, the other gliding unif=
ormly parallel to itself. (<em>See</em> <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.c=
om/topic/Trisecting-the-Angle-The-Quadratrix-of-Hippias-1688521" class=3D"m=
d-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Sidebar: Trisecting the Angle: The=
 Quadratrix of Hippias</a>.)</p><!--[MOD6]--><span class=3D"marker MOD6 mod=
-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD7]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD7 mod-inline">=
</span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">The trick for trisection is an applicat=
ion of what the Greeks called <em><span id=3D"ref726498"></span>neusis</em>=
, a maneuvering of a measured length into a special position to complete a =
geometrical figure. A late version of its use, <a class=3D"md-dictionary-li=
nk md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"ascribed" href=3D"https://www.brit=
annica.com/dictionary/ascribed" data-type=3D"EB">ascribed</a> to <a href=3D=
"https://www.britannica.com/biography/Archimedes" class=3D"md-crosslink " d=
ata-show-preview=3D"true">Archimedes</a> (<em>c.</em> 285=E2=80=93212/211 <=
span class=3D"text-smallcaps">bce</span>), exemplifies the method of angle =
trisection. (<em>See</em> <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Trise=
cting-the-Angle-Archimedes-Method-724632" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show=
-preview=3D"true">Sidebar: Trisecting the Angle: Archimedes=E2=80=99 Method=
</a>.)</p><!--[MOD7]--><span class=3D"marker MOD7 mod-inline"></span> </sec=
tion> <div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"4=
" id=3D"ref217480" data-has-spy=3D"true"> <h2 class=3D"h4">Squaring the cir=
cle</h2> <!--[PREMOD8]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD8 mod-inline"></span><=
p class=3D"topic-paragraph">The pre-Euclidean Greek geometers transformed t=
he practical problem of determining the area of a <span id=3D"ref726499"></=
span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/circle-mathematics" clas=
s=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">circle</a> into a tool of di=
scovery. Three approaches can be distinguished: Hippocrates=E2=80=99 dodge =
of substituting one problem for another; the application of a mechanical in=
strument, as in Hippias=E2=80=99s device for trisecting the angle; and the =
technique that proved the most fruitful, the closer and closer approximatio=
n to an unknown magnitude difficult to study (e.g., the area of a circle) b=
y a series of known magnitudes easier to study (e.g., areas of polygons)=E2=
=80=94a technique known in modern times as the =E2=80=9C<span id=3D"ref7265=
38"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/method-of-exhausti=
on" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">method of exhaustion=
</a>=E2=80=9D and <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" d=
ata-term=3D"attributed" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/attri=
buted" data-type=3D"EB">attributed</a> by its greatest practitioner, Archim=
edes, to Plato=E2=80=99s student <span id=3D"ref726541"></span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.britannica.com/biography/Eudoxus-of-Cnidus" class=3D"md-crosslin=
k " data-show-preview=3D"true">Eudoxus of Cnidus</a> (<em>c.</em> 408=E2=80=
=93<em>c.</em> 355 <span class=3D"text-smallcaps">bce</span>).</p><!--[MOD8=
]--><span class=3D"marker MOD8 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD9]--><span cl=
ass=3D"marker PREMOD9 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">While=
 not able to square the circle, Hippocrates did demonstrate the quadratures=
 of lunes; that is, he showed that the area between two intersecting circul=
ar arcs could be expressed exactly as a rectilinear area and so raised the =
expectation that the circle itself could be treated similarly. (<em>See</em=
> <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Quadrature-of-the-Lune-168852=
4" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Sidebar: Quadrature o=
f the Lune</a>.) A contemporary of Hippias=E2=80=99s discovered that the qu=
adratrix could be used to almost rectify circles. These were the substituti=
on and mechanical approaches.</p><!--[MOD9]--><span class=3D"marker MOD9 mo=
d-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD10]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD10 mod-inlin=
e"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">The method of exhaustion as develope=
d by Eudoxus approximates a curve or <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/=
science/surface-geometry" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-previe=
w=3D"true">surface</a> by using polygons with calculable perimeters and are=
as. As the number of sides of a regular <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.c=
om/science/polygon-mathematics" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-=
preview=3D"true">polygon</a> inscribed in a circle increases indefinitely, =
its perimeter and area =E2=80=9Cexhaust,=E2=80=9D or take up, the circumfer=
ence and area of the circle to within any assignable <a href=3D"https://www=
.britannica.com/science/error-mathematics" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref "=
 data-show-preview=3D"true">error</a> of length or area, however small. In =
Archimedes=E2=80=99 usage, the method of exhaustion produced upper and lowe=
r bounds for the <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" da=
ta-term=3D"value" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/value" data=
-type=3D"EB">value</a> of =CF=80, the ratio of any circle=E2=80=99s circumf=
erence to its diameter. This he accomplished by inscribing a polygon within=
 a circle, and circumscribing a polygon around it as well, thereby bounding=
 the circle=E2=80=99s circumference between the polygons=E2=80=99 calculabl=
e perimeters. He used polygons with 96 sides and thus bound =CF=80 between =
3<span class=3D"md-fraction md-fraction-oblique"><span><span class=3D"md-fr=
ac-num">10</span><span class=3D"md-fraction-symbol">/</span><span class=3D"=
